<paragraph id="8BD236DDEFA93ACDFF78F858FC43FA12" blockId="248.[136,778,1295,2070]" lastBlockId="248.[810,1452,1295,1491]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
Legs 1–4 with 3-segmented rami (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EFA93ACDFD87F858FD7DF871" box="[578,696,1941,1968]" captionStart="FIGURE 165" captionStartId="247.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[234,1358,215,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-18@247.[192,1396,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="247" captionText="FIGURE 165. Bonnierilla similis Illg &amp; Dudley, 1961, female. A, habitus, right; B, caudal ramus; C, rostrum; D, antenna; E, distal part of antenna; F, mandible; G, paragnath; H, maxillule; I, maxilla; J, maxilliped; K, leg 1. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, D, F, H-K, 0.05 mm; C, 0.1 mm; E, G, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591596/files/figure.png" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Fig. 165K</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13562A58EFA93ACDFD01F85BFF58F813" captionStart="FIGURE 166" captionStartId="248.[136,245,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[184,1402,208,1088]" captionTargetId="figure-436@248.[136,1451,182,1120]" captionTargetPageId="248" captionText="FIGURE 166. Bonnierilla similis Illg &amp; Dudley, 1961, female. A, leg 2; B, leg 4; C, right leg 5; D, left leg 5. Scale bars: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591599" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591599/files/figure.png" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">166A, B</figureCitation>
). Inner coxal seta absent in legs 1 and 2, but large seta present in legs 3 and 4. Outer setaon basis slightly shorter than exopod in leg 1 and very small in legs 2–4. Inner distal spine on basis of leg 1 slightly longer than first endopodal segment. Exopod twice as long as endopod in legs 2 and 3, and about 2.4 timeslongerthan endopod in leg 4. Outerspinesonexopods of legs 2–4 very small, mostly rudimentary. Armature formula for legs 1–4 as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEFA93ACDFC9AF904FA58F871" blockId="248.[810,1452,1737,2070]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
Leg 5 (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EFA93ACDFC6AF907FB86F925" box="[943,1091,1737,1764]" captionStart="FIGURE 166" captionStartId="248.[136,245,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[184,1402,208,1088]" captionTargetId="figure-436@248.[136,1451,182,1120]" captionTargetPageId="248" captionText="FIGURE 166. Bonnierilla similis Illg &amp; Dudley, 1961, female. A, leg 2; B, leg 4; C, right leg 5; D, left leg 5. Scale bars: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591599" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591599/files/figure.png" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Fig. 166C, D</figureCitation>
) comprising short protopod and free exopod; protopod withnaked outerdistal seta; exopod with naked setaon apex plus 3 or 4 groups of spinules on inner margin; in dissected specimen left exopod more slender than right, 4.24 times longer than wide (144×34 μm); right exopod 3.68 times longerthan wide (140×38 μm): apical seta slightly shorter than exopodal segment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEFA93ACDFC9AF876FBE5F813" blockId="248.[810,1452,1737,2070]" box="[863,1056,1976,2002]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEFA93ACDFC9AF876FC59F813" bold="true" box="[863,924,1976,2002]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556EFA93ACCFC9AF814FD73FE8E" lastPageId="249" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEFA93ACCFC9AF814FD73FE8E" blockId="248.[810,1452,1737,2070]" lastBlockId="249.[136,778,173,335]" lastPageId="249" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEFA93ACDFC9AF814FC09F835" bold="true" box="[863,972,2010,2036]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species has a characteristic feature that serves to differentiate it from all of its congeners, the 3 strong rod-shaped distal setae on the distal margin of the antenna. Originally this species was reported from 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEFA83ACCFD00FF1EFE58FECA" authority="Alder, 1863" authorityName="Alder" authorityYear="1863" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Pyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="squamulosa">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEFA83ACCFD00FF1EFECBFECA" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">Pyura squamulosa</emphasis>
Alder, 1863
</taxonomicName>
collected on the Mediterranean coast of 
<collectingCountry id="F37A764DEFA83ACCFF2EFEDDFEF2FEEC" box="[235,311,275,301]" name="France" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">France</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEFA83ACCFE8DFEDDFDF0FEEF" author="Illg, P. L. &amp; Dudley, P. L." box="[328,565,275,302]" journalOrPublisher="Vie et Milieu, Supplement" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" pagination="1 - 126" part="12" refId="ref329073" refString="Illg, P. L. &amp; Dudley, P. L. (1961) Notodelphyid copepods from Banyuls-sur Mer. Vie et Milieu, Supplement 12, 1 - 126." title="Notodelphyid copepods from Banyuls-sur Mer" type="journal article" year="1961">Illg &amp; Dudley, 1961</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEFA83ACCFD8EFEDDFF16FE8E" author="Holmes, J. M. C. &amp; Gotto, R. V." journalOrPublisher="The Irish Naturalists' Journal" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" pagination="340 - 343" part="22" refId="ref328755" refString="Holmes, J. M. C. &amp; Gotto, R. V. (1987) Some ascidicolous copepods new to British and Irish waters. The Irish Naturalists' Journal, 22 (8), 340 - 343." title="Some ascidicolous copepods new to British and Irish waters" type="journal article" year="1987">Holmes &amp; Gotto (1987)</bibRefCitation>
subsequently reported it from Irish waters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
